{
  "slug": "as-of-july-2026-financial-and-bankruptcy-status-of-6c2b2dbf",
  "query": "As of July 2026, financial and bankruptcy status of these companies: Chegg Inc, America's Car-Mart Inc, JetBlue Airways, Peloton Inc, Faraday Future Intelligent Electric, Petco Health and Wellness. Which are at highest risk of bankruptcy filing in mid-2026? Any going concern warnings, debt maturities, or restructuring news?",
  "answer": "I've completed the research. Here's a summary of the key findings:\n\n## Which are at highest bankruptcy risk in mid-2026?\n\n**Two companies carry genuine near-term risk:**\n\n1. **Faraday Future (FFAI) \u2014 HIGHEST RISK.** Explicit going-concern warning in its Q1 2026 10-Q, only **$12.2M cash**, ~$76M negative working capital, and management stated it **\"will likely seek bankruptcy protection unless it can secure new funding.\"** Q1 revenue was just $512K against a $42.3M loss. Also facing Nasdaq delisting (stock $0.19, deadline Sept 16, 2026).\n\n2. **America's Car-Mart (CRMT) \u2014 VERY HIGH RISK.** In **lender forbearance** on defaults (window through early Sept 2026, extendable to Nov 2026), running a formal strategic-alternatives review with **Houlihan Lokey**, and explicitly disclosing a **\"potential need to seek bankruptcy or insolvency protection.\"** Q3 FY2026 net loss of -$76.7M, tight $5\u20137M minimum-liquidity covenants, ~31% of dealerships closed.\n\n**The other four are lower risk:**\n\n3. **Chegg (CHGG)** \u2014 Distressed business (revenue -48% YoY from AI disruption) but only a small $33.9M note due Sept 2026 vs. $67.9M cash; risk is medium-term/strategic, no formal going-concern warning.\n\n4. **JetBlue (JBLU)** \u2014 Slow-burn credit story: six years of losses, CCC+ rating, analysts cite ~75% bankruptcy odds by 2027, but $2.4B liquidity makes a mid-2026 filing unlikely; the real wall is 2027\u20132029.\n\n5. **Petco (WOOF)** \u2014 Just refinanced (Feb 2026), maturities pushed to 2031, stabilizing. Low risk.\n\n6. **Peloton (PTON)** \u2014 Turnaround succeeding, first-ever positive net income expected FY2026, net debt cut ~70% to $173M, $1.13B cash. Low risk.\n\n**Note:** AskNews was unavailable (credit limit), so qualitative news came via web search cross-referenced against the financial-data tools; full sources and data points are in the structured output.",
